er organs and the digestive process acted as counterpoints to politeness and other modes of refined sociability, drawing attention to the deeper workings of the self. Moving beyond recent studies of luxury and conspicuous consumption, where dysfunctional bowels have been represented as a symptom of excess, this book seeks to explore other manifestations of the visceral and to explain how the bowels played a crucial part in eighteenth-century emotions and perceptions of the self. The collection offers an interdisciplinary and cross-cultural perspective on entrails and digestion by addressing urban history, visual studies, literature, medical history, religious history, and material culture in England, France, and Germany.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnlightenment. 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 0aSelf. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aFrance.  aGermany.  aburlesque bellies.  adysfunctional bowels.  aeighteenth century.  ahuman digestion.  ahuman entrails.  amaterial culture.  aurban history.  aviscera.1 aArmand, Guilhem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAznavour, Clémence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarles, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr, Rebecca Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr, Rebecca Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuillerme, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGélis, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenner, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJu